Discrete Probability Calculations

Zihan Fang

9/19/2020

0.1 Introduction

The world series is a best-of-7 match-up between the champions of the American and National Leagues of Major League Baseball. In this blog, I am going to explain probability calculations related to the world series.

0.2 Background

I will use the rules of probability and discrete probability functions to show you how I solve the following questions.

Setup: 1.Suppose that the Braves and the Yankees are teams competing in the World Series. 2.Suppose that in any given game, the probability that the Braves win is PB and the probability that the Yankees win is PY=1−PB.

Stopping Rule: To win the World Series which is a best-of-7 match-up, Braves have to win 4 matches, and the World Series will stop when Braves win the 4th match.

0.3 Methods

0.3.1 1.What is the probability that the Braves win the World Series given that PB=0.55?

If the Braves win the World Series, they have to win at least 4 matches, and the probability they win is 0.55. I use pnbinom() that means they lose three or fewer matches before they win four matches. The probability that the Braves win the World Series given that PB=0.55 is 0.6082878.

pnbinom(3,4,0.55)
## [1] 0.6082878

0.3.2 2.What is the probability that the Braves win the World Series given that PB=x? This will be a figure (see below) with PB on the x-axis and P(Braves win World Series) on the y-axis.

Now the PB is not defined yet, so I would assume the x could be any number between 0 to 1.

x<-seq(0,1,by=0.001)
prob.win1<-pnbinom(3,4,x)
plot(x,prob.win1,main="Probability of winning the World Series",
     xlab = "Probability of the Braves winning a head-to-head matchup",
     ylab = "P(Win World Series)",
     type = "l")
abline(h=0.5,col="red")

The probability of the Braves winning a head-to-head matchup(PB) is x now, PB could be between 0 and 1, I also set the increment of as 0.001 to make the results more accurate. From this graphic we can see PB on the x-axis and P(Braves win World Series) on the y-axis, P(Braves win World Series) depends on the PB. When PB is smaller than 0.5, it is less likely for Braves win World Series. When PB is larger than 0.5, it is more likely for Braves win World Series. We can also see a clear growth trend when PB is larger than 0.2 and smaller than 0.8.

0.3.3 3.Suppose one could change the World Series to be best-of-9 or some other best-of-X series. What is the shortest series length so that P(Braves win World Series| PB=0.55)≥0.8

In this question, the series length is not defined and the series length should be an odd number. We already have the assumption: PB= 0.55.

To win the World Series, if it is best-of-9, the winner has to win 5 matches and lose 4 or fewer matches, if it is best-of-11, the winner has to win 6 matches and lose 5 or fewer matches. In this way, we can set the number of wins (numwin) and the number of loss (numloss) would be the number of wins minus 1 (numwin-1) or fewer.

We have calculated in question 1: when PB=0.55, the probability of Braves win World Series is 0.6083 which is less than 0.8. Thus, the shortest series length must be more than 7 and the least number of wins must be more than 4, so I will set the sequence of the number of wins as 4 to 100. I use pnbinom to calculate the probability of Braves win World Series. And the World Series length (len.ser) would be the number of wins (numwin) plus the number of loss (numloss).

numwin = seq(4,100,by=1)
numloss = numwin-1
probwins= pnbinom(numloss,numwin,0.55)
len.ser=numloss+numwin
len.ser[which(probwins>= 0.8)][1]
## [1] 71

From the results, we can know when P(Braves win World Series| PB=0.55)≥0.8, the shortest World Series length is 71.

I also plot a graph.

plot(len.ser,probwins,
     main = "Probability of winning the World Series",
     xlab = "World Series Length",
     ylab = "P(Braves Win World Series | p=0.55)",
     type = "l")
abline(h=0.8,col="red")

From this graph, we can see a clear positive correlation between World Series Length and P(Braves Win World Series|PB=0.55), and we can find the shortest length when P(Braves Win World Series| PB=0.55)>=0.8.

0.3.4 4.What is the shortest series length so that P(Braves win World Series| PB=x) ≥ 0.8? This will be a figure (see below) with PB on the x-axis and series length is the y-axis.

In this question, both PB and world series length have not be defined, so I would assume PB could be any number from 0.51 to 1 and the increment is 0.001. Then I create a for loop to record the series length and find the shortest length.

probbwin = seq(0.51,1,by=0.001)
shortlen = NA
for(i in 1:length(probbwin)){
  num.win=seq(1,100,by=1)
  num.loss=num.win-1
  pws=pnbinom(num.loss,num.win,probbwin[i])
  len.ser=num.win+num.loss
  shortlen[i]= len.ser[which(pws>=0.8)[1]]
}

From the table above, we can find the longest series and shortest series. And the shortest series length is 1.

Then, I will draw a figure to show the relationship.

plot(probbwin,shortlen,type = "l",
     main=expression("Shortest series: P(Braves Win World Series | p=x )">=0.8),
     xlab="Probability of Braves win World Series",
     ylab="Series Length")

From this graph, we can see when PB is increasing, the shortest series length will decrease, when the probability of the Braves win the World Series is more than 0.8 and even approaching 1, the shortest series length is 1.

0.3.5 5.Calculate P(PB=0.55|Braves win World Series in 7 games) under the assumption that either PB=0.55 or PB=0.45. Explain your solution.

For this question, we should learn about Bayes’ theorem first: \[P(A|B)=\frac{P(B|A)P(A)}{P(B)}\]

So, we have to calculate P(Braves win World Series in 7 games|PB=0.55), P(PB=0.55), P(Braves win World Series in 7 games).

From the question 1, we can get the P(Braves win World Series in 7 games|PB=0.55) = 0.1667701. And there is an assumption that either PB=0.55 or PB=0.45, so P(PB=0.55) = P(PB=0.45) = 0.5

#probability that Braves win the World Series in 7 games given that Pb=0.55
dnbinom(3,4,0.55)
## [1] 0.1667701

Then, based on the assumption that either PB=0.55 or PB=0.45, we can calculate the P(Braves win World Series in 7 games) = P(Braves win World Series in 7 games|PB=0.55)xP(PB=0.55)+P(Braves win World Series in 7 games|PB=0.45)xP(PB=0.45) = 0.1516092

#P(Braves win World Series in 7 games)
dnbinom(3,4,0.45)*0.5+dnbinom(3,4,0.55)*0.5
## [1] 0.1516092

Finally, we can solve the problem using Bayes’ formula and get the answer 0.55

#P(Pb=0.55|Braves win World Series in 7 games) under the assumption that either Pb=0.55 or Pb=0.45
dnbinom(3,4,0.55)*0.5/(dnbinom(3,4,0.45)*0.5+dnbinom(3,4,0.55)*0.5)
## [1] 0.55
